                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I <rs id="t17800628-127-viclabel631" type="occupation">keep a shop</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17800628-127-victim1668 t17800628-127-viclabel631"></join> in <placeName id="t17800628-127-crimeloc632">Tottenham-court road</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17800628-127-crimeloc632" type="placeName" value="Tottenham-court road"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17800628-127-crimeloc632" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17800628-127-off629 t17800628-127-crimeloc632"></join>. On Saturday the 13th of May, about half after ten at night, I was in the shop; I heard a pane of glass break; they had fastened the shop-door on the out-side with a cord; a person who saw the prisoner run from the window, pursued him, and brought him back in about two minutes; his finger was cut, and bled very much; he was searched, but nothing found upon him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-127-person1670">
                  MATTHEW
                   WEST
               <interp inst="t17800628-127-person1670" type="surname" value="WEST"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-127-person1670" type="given" value="MATTHEW"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-127-person1670" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>Coming down Tottenham court road, on the 13th of May, about half after ten o'clock, I heard a window break. I looked across the way, and saw the prisoner run. I ran after him, and made a blow at him, at the top of Tavistock-street; he popped his head down, and ran back again down the mews in Tavistock-street, there I knocked him down and secured him, and brought him back to the prosecutor's house; there was nothing found upon him. I saw nobody else run from the window; his finger was off before, the stump was cut with the glass.</p>
               <p>Jones. The lace mentioned in the indictment was lost out of the window. I saw it about half an hour before. There were thirteen yards at half a crown a yard; it was on a card; it was picked up by a gentleman.</p>
               <p>JOHN BROWN sworn.</p>
               <p>On the 13th of May, between ten and eleven o'clock, coming down Tottenham-court road, I saw a mob at the prosecutor's house, and in Tavistock-street I found this card of lace (producing it). I took it back to the prosecutor's; he said it was his property.</p>
               <p>(The lace was deposed to by the prosecutor.)</p>
               <p>PRISONER's DEFENCE.</p>
               <p>Coming down Tavistock-street three boys ran by me, a gentleman laid hold of me, and said I had stolen a piece of lace. I know nothing of it.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17800628-127-verdict633" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17800628-127-verdict633" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
